{"key":"post-10782419","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10782419</id>\n<content>84F is too hot to colonize mycelium.&amp;nbsp; The old advice of 86F was incorrect and actually slows down colonization and increases rate of contamination.&amp;nbsp; Don't let the ambient temp go over 80.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You can colonize your substrates on an open shelf at normal room temperature.&amp;nbsp; Spawn your grains into the manure, cover with foil, and set them on a bookshelf for ten days to two weeks.&amp;nbsp; When fully colonized, let them set for an additional few days to a week.&amp;nbsp; I like to wait a week, because I've found eventual flush and finished product weight is better.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Temp drop is not a pinning trigger with cubes.&amp;nbsp; You can colonize and fruit at the same temp.&amp;nbsp; When fruiting time comes, you want lots of fresh air and 95% or better humidity.&amp;nbsp; If you can do that with perlite, fine.&amp;nbsp; If you use a humidifier, put it on a timer so it doesn't saturate your substrates.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Evaporation of moisture from the substrate is a major pinning trigger, so that's why you want a lot of fresh air.&amp;nbsp; Mist a few times daily as required to replace the moisture that is lost.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Don't use incandescent lamps.&amp;nbsp; Use fluorescent, and look for 'natural daylight' or 6500K on the label.&amp;nbsp; A bright window also works well.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10782450</next>\n<prev>10782417</prev>\n<first>10781475</first>\n<last>10792612</last>\n<when>1249181210</when>\n<utime>08/02/09 05:46 AM</utime>\n</post>"}